1. Overview and Significance
This project tackles challenge of antimicrobial resistance by testing whether whole-genome sequence patterns
can predict resistance without relying solely on known AMR genes. It connects to key topics including k-mer
genome representation and ML classification for rapid AMR prediction.
2. Data Description
Publicly available bacterial genomes were obtained from BV-BRC/PATRIC, using whole-genome FASTA
sequence files and antibiotic resistance CSV/TSV phenotype labels. After downloading through the PATRIC
interface, we filtered out isolates with missing metadata, standardized genome IDs, and extracted k-mer
frequency features from each cleaned genome.
3. Methods / Analysis Plan
We will extract k-mer frequency features from whole-genome FASTA files using Python/Biopython and train
machine-learning classifiers to predict Resistant vs Sensitive phenotypes. Model performance will be evaluated
using accuracy, F1-score, and ROC-AUC, and key predictive k-mers will be interpreted using feature importance
or SHAP values.
4. Expected Deliverables
We will produce a Jupyter notebook/Python script that performs k-mer extraction, ML model training, and
evaluation, along with figures such as ROC curves and feature-importance plots. A short report will summarize
methods, results, and biological interpretation, and all code and data-processing steps will be organized in a
reproducible GitHub repository.
5. Anticipated Challenges & Mitigation
A potential obstacle is the large size of FASTA genomes; we will address this by using smaller k-mers and
subsampling isolates if necessary. Another challenge is class imbalance in resistance labels, which we will
mitigate using stratified splits and class-weighted ML models.
6. Timeline (3-Week Plan)
Week
Tasks / Milestones
1
Download FASTA genomes and labels, preprocess data, and extract k-mer features.
2
Train and tune ML models (XGBoost/SVM) and evaluate performance (ROC-AUC, F1).
3
Create visualizations, interpret top k-mers, and finalize the report and repository.
7. Evaluation / Success Criteria
Success will be measured by completing a fully reproducible workflow that extracts k-mers, trains ML models, and
produces interpretable outputs. The project is successful if the model achieves ROC-AUC ≥ 0.75 and its top k-`
match known or biologically plausible AMR-related regions.
8. AI Use & Reproducibility Statement (required)
ChatGPT was used only to assist in creating the 1-page project summary by helping condense detailed project
information, suggesting clear structure and flow, and generating ideas for organizing sections logically within the
page limit. AI outputs will be verified manually by checking datasets, rerunning code, and confirming biological
accuracy with BV-BRC/CARD. All prompts, AI outputs, and validated revisions will be recorded in a GitHub
ai_usage.md file for full transparency and reproducibility.
